From grace@techcorp.com Wed Jan 15 09:30:00 2025
From: Grace Okonkwo <grace@techcorp.com>
To: engineering@techcorp.com
Subject: RFC: switching from REST to GraphQL for the public API
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 2025 09:30:00 -0500
Message-ID: <rfc-001@techcorp.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8

Engineering team,

I'm proposing we consider GraphQL for the next major version of our public API. Key motivations:

- Over-fetching: mobile clients currently download 4–10x more data than they need because REST endpoints return full objects.
- Versioning: we're already on v3 of several endpoints after schema changes. GraphQL schemas are additive.
- Developer experience: customers have asked for a single endpoint with introspection.

Downsides I see: learning curve for the team, potential N+1 query issues if we don't implement DataLoader, and existing SDK breakage.

Seeking feedback before I write a full proposal. Thoughts?

Grace

From bob@techcorp.com Wed Jan 15 13:15:00 2025
From: Bob Martinez <bob@techcorp.com>
To: grace@techcorp.com
Cc: engineering@techcorp.com
Subject: Re: RFC: switching from REST to GraphQL for the public API
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 2025 13:15:00 -0500
Message-ID: <rfc-002@techcorp.com>
In-Reply-To: <rfc-001@techcorp.com>
References: <rfc-001@techcorp.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8

Grace,

I'm broadly supportive but the N+1 problem is real and has bitten us before. DataLoader is a must if we go this route.

Also worth noting: our biggest enterprise customer (Acme Corp) has deeply integrated with the v3 REST API. Any migration would need at minimum a 12-month deprecation window.

Alternative suggestion: could we offer GraphQL as a parallel interface without deprecating REST? Some companies (GitHub, Shopify) do this successfully.

Bob

